rows.text: During WW2 aircraft maintenance units tried using this airfield for storage purposes but apparently it was often water-logged. There is a story that six Blackburn Botha types flown in to Ansty from Hawarden in February 1940 may have sunk in so deep they were never rescued.
A Tiger Moth of 9 EFTS was landing when it collided with another Tiger Moth on the ground. Both were burnt out, but there were no casualties.
Tiger Moths N5456 and N5472 of 9 EFTS are recorded as crashing.
Tiger Moth N6649 of 9 EFTS hit a bus on approach.
A pair of Tiger Moths from 9 EFTS collided in the air at Whitley.
A pair of Tiger Moths from 9 EFTS collided near the airfield
Tiger Moth R4921 of 9 EFTS crashed near the airfield after engine failure.
